Name>Frederic</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Bouder</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=RES-173-27-0103"><gtr:id>68A549FD-AE31-447B-BF49-E69BA99CED1E</gtr:id><gtr:title>The Development of Guidance for Civil Servants on Risk, With a Particular Focus on Risk Communication</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-173-27-0103</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This fellowship at the Risk and Regulation Advisory Council and the Government Office for Science draws on forty years of risk research to improve Government' risk communication. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>Risk scares can have a devastating impact. When not properly addressed, they generate distrust with the effect of challenging proportionate and cost-effective decision-making. High profile scandals&amp;nbsp;- eg BSE, and controversies -&amp;nbsp;eg MMR&amp;nbsp; have demonstrated the destructive effects of poor risk communication. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>Excellent and comprehensive guidance already exists. Yet, decision makers and civil servants do not use this knowledge on a routine basis.&amp;nbsp; Well-crafted top-down messages are not sufficient anymore.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>This project concentrates on helping civil servants and decision-makers successfully engage in a two-way communication practice. The project departs from the unsuccessful tendency to focus on 'behavioural prescription'. Three complementary outputs are developed that may support organisational change, without expecting to change the competencies of anyone who reads it: &lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>A risk communication 'survivor's guide' with 5 key messages designed to organise this process, presented in a user-friendly format&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Critical questions and concrete examples of risk situations, which provide direction on how to implement&amp;nbsp; the key message&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Three brief case studies with detailed discussion of specific risks -&amp;nbsp;ie nanotechnology, flooding and obesity.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

